args: Whoa! I just thought we'd drop by this\nrestaurant for a bite to eat before we head\nout, but wow, that was some shout...

For real. I heard this bistro was pretty
popular, but I didn't think they were at the
＂screamin' at people to leave＂ level.
Hold up, look—somebody just came out!
I haven't seen you since the Orichalcum\nChef kerfuffle.
Yeah, I still owe you big-time for that.\nNice to run into you again, though!
The feeling is mutual. I would've\nthought you'd returned home to\nyour family's restaurant by now.
Not yet. I can't return to Nanakusa\nuntil I've honed flavors that stack\nup to my late father's.
When we lost him, the restaurant's\nreputation started going down the drain.\nIt falls to me to set things right.

I remember you saying as much.
That's quite the legacy to live up to.
Oh! Sorry to change the subject, but is
everything okay? We heard shouting.
Yeeeah, about that... I miiight have\noverstepped just a smidge.
And now, my trainees, I shall instruct\nyou in the fine art of soup-making!\nFirst, we will peel these shrimp...
Excuse me, chef! Shrimp tend to shrink\nand get tough when you boil them. We\ncould reduce that if we left them unpeeled.
Y'know, I think she's onto something.\nMy shrimp ARE getting a tad too chewy.

A-ahem! Curb your whispering, please!
Next, we'll prepare the onions. If you cut
one along the fibers, the onion will remain
whole as it boils, making the broth—

Um, chef! It's a soup, so I'm not sure we
need to be worried about it falling apart.
If we cut ACROSS the fibers instead,
it'll mellow out the pungent onion flavor.

Grrrgh... I do believe I'M the one leading
the lesson right now! Now, let's discuss
how to prepare a quality soup stock.
Using a beef bone as our base, we'll—

That's a big no-go, chef! The bone will
overpower the other flavors of our
carefully chosen ingredients. I'd advise
boiling the shellfish in a vegetable broth.
Hey! What do you think you're—
...Aaand done! A delicious shrimp soup\nthat pays respect to each and every\nfarm-fresh ingredient!

Holy minestrone! It's like the chef's soup,
only the flavors are ratcheted up to eleven!
How did she do that using literally the
same ingredients?
The ingredients might be the same, \nbut flavor starts at the base, working its\nway upward to mouthfeel and presentation.
The true essence of cooking is matching\nseasonings with ingredients to draw out\nhidden flavors in every single dish!
MITSUBA! I want you out of my restaurant,\nnow! GEEEEET OUT!
So the yell was you getting fired.
Yeah. I kinda brought it upon myself,\nthough. Shouldn't have showed up the\nhead chef like that.
Honestly, though? I think staying\nquiet would've been even worse.
It would've been a disgrace to both the\ningredients AND the people eating them!
You sure never compromise when\nit comes to cooking, Mitsuba.\nBut what are you going to do now?
Honestly? I'm at a loss. It was a live-in job\nsituation, so I'm kinda out on the street.
I see. Well, how about you come to the\nHalidom? I can offer you room and board,\nat the very least.
Really?! You are a LIFESAVER!\nBut, er, are you sure it's all right?

Perfectly fine with me. Mind you, we
do seem to find ourselves embroiled in
one conflict after another these days,
but as long as that's okay with you...
Pfft, I can handle a scrap or three.\nHeck, I'll take on all comers if it means I'll\nbe able to continue my culinary training!
Now there's the Mitsuba I know.\nC'mon, then—we'll show you to the castle.
Hold up, folks, rewind a sec!\nHappy reunion and all, but I think you're\nforgettin' that Papa Bear is HUNGRY!
Oh, yeah, that's actually the whole\nreason why we were in the area.\nCare to join us, Mitsuba?
All right! Where to, then? Oh! I know!\nI heard they recently opened a\nHinomoto-style joint around here!

Ooh, just like we serve at Nanakusa!
Wild that there's a place in Alberia
that does Hinomotoan cuisine.
I wonder what they've got on the menu.
Sounds like Mitsuba's on board,\nso let's head on over!
＂Seven Leaves: Creative Hinomotoan\nCuisine.＂ I think this is the place!
Yup. Place's got a sterling rep. It checks\nall the boxes: quick, cheap, and delicious.
Why, do my eyes deceive me?\nIf it isn't my sister, Mitsuba.
Er, care to introduce us, Mitsuba?
This is Nazuna, fourth of the Nanakusa\nchildren...and my younger sister.
Little sister, huh? She looks pretty darn\nflashy for the daughter of a traditional\nHinomotoan joint.
Why is your restaurant HERE, Nazuna?
Why indeed? I guess you could say I'm\ndoing preliminary work for my worldwide\nexpansion.
You know, so I can crush Nanakusa.
